{'answer': 'At the time personal data are obtained from the data subject, the controller shall provide: 1) Identity and contact details of the controller and their representative; 2) Contact details of the data protection officer; 3) Purposes of processing and the legal basis; 4) Legitimate interests pursued if based on Article 6(1)(f); 5) Recipients or categories of recipients; 6) Details on transfers to third countries/international organisations and adequacy decisions. Additionally, to ensure fair and transparent processing, the controller shall provide: the storage period or criteria to determine it; the right to withdraw consent; the right to access, rectification, erasure, restriction, object to processing, and data portability; the right to lodge a complaint with a supervisory authority; whether data provision is a statutory/contractual requirement; and the existence of automated decision-making, including profiling.', 'full_answer': "According to Article 13, when personal data are collected from the data subject, the controller is mandated to provide specific information at the time of acquisition. Under paragraph 1, this includes the identity and contact details of the controller and their representative, the data protection officer's contact details, the purposes and legal basis for processing, the legitimate interests pursued (if applicable under Article 6(1)(f)), the recipients of the data, and information regarding transfers to third countries or international organisations, including adequacy decisions or safeguards. 

Furthermore, paragraph 2 requires additional information to ensure fair and transparent processing: the storage period (or criteria for its determination), the right to withdraw consent (where applicable), the rights to access, rectification, erasure, restriction of processing, objection, and data portability, the right to lodge a complaint with a supervisory authority, and whether the provision of data is a statutory or contractual requirement (including consequences of failure to provide). It also requires disclosure of automated decision-making, including profiling, and the logic and consequences involved. 

Notably, paragraph 3 requires that if data are further processed for a different purpose, the subject must be informed prior to that processing. However, paragraph 4 specifies that these obligations do not apply if the data subject already possesses the information.", 'key_snippet': 'the controller shall, at the time when personal data are obtained, provide the data subject with all of the following information', 'chunks': ['chapter III, article 13, point 1', 'chapter III, article 13, point 2', 'chapter III, article 13, point 1a', 'chapter III, article 13, point 1b', 'chapter III, article 13, point 1c', 'chapter III, article 13, point 1d', 'chapter III, article 13, point 1e', 'chapter III, article 13, point 1f', 'chapter III, article 13, point 2a', 'chapter III, article 13, point 2b', 'chapter III, article 13, point 2c', 'chapter III, article 13, point 2d', 'chapter III, article 13, point 2e', 'chapter III, article 13, point 2f'], 'percentage': ['10', '10', '10', '10', '10', '10', '10', '10', '10', '10', '10', '10', '10', '10']}

{'answer': 'Article 20 of the GDPR grants the data subject the right to data portability. This allows the subject to receive personal data they provided to a controller in a structured, commonly used, and machine-readable format, and the right to transmit those data to another controller without hindrance. Additionally, the data subject has the right to have the personal data transmitted directly from one controller to another, where technically feasible. This right applies when processing is carried out by automated means and is based on consent (pursuant to Article 6(1)(a) or Article 9(2)(a)) or on a contract (pursuant to Article 6(1)(b)). The exercise of this right shall be without prejudice to Article 17 and shall not apply to processing necessary for tasks in the public interest or the exercise of official authority, nor shall it adversely affect the rights and freedoms of others.', 'full_answer': 'Pursuant to Article 20 of the GDPR, the data subject is granted the right to data portability. This right is composed of two primary capabilities: first, the right to receive the personal data they provided to a controller in a format that is structured, commonly used, and machine-readable; second, the right to transmit those data to another controller without hindrance from the original controller. Furthermore, paragraph 2 specifies that the data subject shall have the right to have their personal data transmitted directly from one controller to another, provided that this is technically feasible. 

For this right to be applicable, two cumulative conditions must be met: 
1. The processing must be based on consent (under Article 6(1)(a) or Article 9(2)(a)) or on a contract (under Article 6(1)(b)); 
2. The processing must be carried out by automated means. 

There are specific limitations to this right: it does not apply to processing necessary for the performance of a task carried out in the public interest or in the exercise of official authority vested in the controller. Additionally, the exercise of this right is without prejudice to Article 17 (right to erasure) and must not adversely affect the rights and freedoms of other individuals.', 'key_snippet': 'The data subject shall have the right to receive the personal data concerning him or her', 'chunks': ['chapter III, article 20, point 1', 'chapter III, article 20, point 2', 'chapter III, article 20, point 3', 'chapter III, article 20, point 4', 'chapter III, article 20, point 1a', 'chapter III, article 20, point 1b'], 'percentage': ['30', '20', '20', '10', '10', '10']}

{'answer': "The controller shall implement appropriate technical and organisational measures to ensure and demonstrate that processing is performed in accordance with the Regulation, taking into account the nature, scope, context, and purposes of processing, as well as the risks of varying likelihood and severity for the rights and freedoms of natural persons (Article 24(1)). These measures must be reviewed and updated where necessary. Additionally, where proportionate to processing activities, such measures shall include the implementation of appropriate data protection policies (Article 24(2)). To demonstrate compliance with the controller's obligations, adherence to approved codes of conduct (Article 40) or approved certification mechanisms (Article 42) may be used (Article 24(3)).", 'full_answer': 'According to Article 24(1), the controller is obligated to implement appropriate technical and organisational measures to ensure and be able to demonstrate that processing is performed in accordance with the GDPR. This implementation must consider the nature, scope, context, and purposes of the processing, as well as the risks of varying likelihood and severity for the rights and freedoms of natural persons. The Regulation explicitly mandates that these measures shall be reviewed and updated where necessary.

Furthermore, Article 24(2) specifies that the implementation of appropriate data protection policies by the controller shall be included among these measures, provided it is proportionate in relation to the processing activities.

To facilitate the demonstration of compliance with these obligations, Article 24(3) provides that the controller may use adherence to approved codes of conduct, as referred to in Article 40, or approved certification mechanisms, as referred to in Article 42, as an element to demonstrate compliance.', 'key_snippet': 'the controller shall implement appropriate technical and organisational measures to ensure and to be able to demonstrate that processing is performed in accordance with this Regulation', 'chunks': ['chapter_iv_article_24'], 'percentage': ['100']}

{'answer': 'According to Article 25, the controller must implement appropriate technical and organisational measures for two purposes: 1) Data protection by design: implemented at the time of determining the means for processing and during processing to integrate necessary safeguards and implement data-protection principles (such as data minimisation) effectively; 2) Data protection by default: to ensure that only personal data necessary for each specific purpose of the processing are processed, covering the amount of data collected, extent of processing, storage period, and accessibility.', 'full_answer': "Under Article 25, the controller is required to implement appropriate technical and organisational measures across two distinct dimensions: 

1. Data Protection by Design: As per paragraph 1, the controller shall implement these measures both at the time of the determination of the means for processing and at the time of the processing itself. These measures (e.g., pseudonymisation) are designed to effectively implement data-protection principles, such as data minimisation, and integrate necessary safeguards to meet Regulation requirements and protect data subjects' rights. This process must account for the state of the art, implementation costs, and the nature, scope, context, purposes, and risks of the processing.

2. Data Protection by Default: As per paragraph 2, the controller shall implement appropriate technical and organisational measures to ensure that, by default, only personal data necessary for each specific purpose of the processing are processed. This obligation specifically applies to the amount of personal data collected, the extent of their processing, the period of their storage, and their accessibility. A key requirement is ensuring that personal data are not made accessible to an indefinite number of natural persons without the individual's intervention.", 'key_snippet': 'the controller shall... implement appropriate technical and organisational measures', 'chunks': ['chapter_iv_article_25'], 'percentage': ['100']}

{'answer': 'According to Article 54(1), each Member State must provide by law for the following six provisions regarding the establishment of the supervisory authority:
(a) the establishment of each supervisory authority;
(b) the qualifications and eligibility conditions required for appointment as a member;
(c) the rules and procedures for the appointment of the member or members;
(d) the duration of the term of the member or members, which shall be no less than four years (with specific exceptions for the first appointment after 24 May 2016 to protect independence via staggered appointments);
(e) whether and for how many terms members are eligible for reappointment;
(f) the conditions governing obligations of members and staff, prohibitions on incompatible actions, occupations, and benefits during and after the term of office, and rules for the cessation of employment.', 'full_answer': "Pursuant to Article 54(1), each Member State is legally obligated to provide for six specific provisions concerning the establishment of its supervisory authority. These include: first, the formal establishment of each supervisory authority; second, the specific qualifications and eligibility conditions that must be met to be appointed as a member; third, the established rules and procedures for the appointment of such members; fourth, the duration of the term of office, which must be at least four years, although the first appointment after 24 May 2016 may be shorter if necessary to ensure the authority's independence through a staggered appointment procedure; fifth, the determination of whether members are eligible for reappointment and the number of terms permitted; and sixth, the conditions governing the obligations of members and staff, including prohibitions on actions, occupations, and benefits that are incompatible with their duties both during and after their term of office, as well as the rules governing the cessation of employment. Additionally, Article 54(2) mandates that members and staff be subject to a duty of professional secrecy regarding confidential information acquired during their tasks, which specifically applies to reporting infringements of the Regulation during their term of office.", 'key_snippet': 'Each Member State shall provide by law for all of the following: (a) the establishment of each supervisory authority', 'chunks': ['chapter_vi_article_54'], 'percentage': ['100']}

{'answer': 'According to Article 57, each supervisory authority shall, on its territory: monitor and enforce the application of the Regulation; promote public awareness of risks, rules, safeguards, and rights (with specific attention to children); advise national parliament and government on legislative/administrative measures; promote awareness of obligations for controllers and processors; provide information to data subjects on their rights; handle and investigate complaints; cooperate and share information with other authorities; conduct investigations; monitor developments in ICT and commercial practices; give advice on processing operations under Article 36(2); maintain lists for impact assessments; encourage and approve codes of conduct and certification mechanisms; draft/publish accreditation criteria; conduct accreditations; authorize contractual clauses; approve binding corporate rules; review certifications; and keep internal records of infringements.', 'full_answer': "Pursuant to Article 57 of the GDPR, each supervisory authority is assigned a comprehensive set of tasks to be performed within its territory. These include the primary responsibility to monitor and enforce the application of the Regulation. They must promote public awareness regarding processing risks, rules, safeguards, and rights, ensuring that activities for children receive specific attention. Their advisory role extends to the national parliament, government, and other bodies regarding legislative and administrative measures for the protection of natural persons' rights. 

Operational duties include providing information to data subjects about their rights, handling and investigating complaints (facilitated by measures like electronic forms), and cooperating with other supervisory authorities to ensure consistent enforcement. They are tasked with conducting investigations, monitoring ICT developments and commercial practices, and providing advice on specific processing operations. 

Furthermore, they manage technical compliance tools by maintaining lists for data protection impact assessments, encouraging and approving codes of conduct, and promoting certification mechanisms. This includes drafting and publishing accreditation criteria, conducting the accreditation of monitoring and certification bodies, and authorizing specific contractual clauses or approving binding corporate rules. They also perform periodic reviews of certifications and maintain internal records of infringements and measures taken. Notably, the performance of these tasks shall be free of charge for data subjects and, where applicable, for data protection officers, although reasonable fees may be charged for manifestly unfounded or excessive requests.", 'key_snippet': 'each supervisory authority shall on its territory: monitor and enforce the application of this Regulation', 'chunks': ['chapter_vi_article_57', 'chapter_vi_article_57'], 'percentage': ['100', '0']}

{'answer': "A supervisory authority may confer investigative powers on the members or staff of a seconding supervisory authority under the following circumstances: 1) the members or staff must be involved in joint operations; 2) the action must be in accordance with Member State law; and 3) the seconding supervisory authority must provide authorization. Alternatively, if the law of the host supervisory authority permits, these members or staff may exercise their own investigative powers according to the law of the seconding supervisory authority's Member State. In both cases, such powers may only be exercised under the guidance and in the presence of members or staff of the host supervisory authority. Additionally, the seconded personnel shall be subject to the Member State law of the host supervisory authority (Article 62(3)).", 'full_answer': "According to Article 62(3), a supervisory authority can confer powers, specifically including investigative powers, on members or staff of a seconding supervisory authority provided they are involved in joint operations. This conferral is subject to two primary conditions: it must be in accordance with Member State law and requires the explicit authorization of the seconding supervisory authority. 

Alternatively, the regulation allows for a different mechanism: if the law of the Member State of the host supervisory authority permits, the members or staff of the seconding authority may exercise their own investigative powers, but these must be exercised in accordance with the law of the Member State of the seconding supervisory authority. 

Regardless of which mechanism is used, there are strict operational constraints: the exercise of these investigative powers is permitted only under the guidance and in the presence of members or staff of the host supervisory authority. Furthermore, the seconding supervisory authority's members or staff are legally subject to the Member State law of the host supervisory authority while operating in that capacity.", 'key_snippet': "A supervisory authority may, in accordance with Member State law, and with the seconding supervisory authority's authorisation, confer powers, including investigative powers", 'chunks': ['chapter_vii_article_62'], 'percentage': ['100']}

{'answer': "Liability for damage caused by processing that infringes the GDPR is distributed as follows: any controller involved in the processing shall be liable. A processor is liable only if it fails to comply with obligations specifically directed to processors or acts outside or contrary to the controller's lawful instructions (Article 82, point 2). A controller or processor may be exempt from liability if they prove they are not in any way responsible for the event causing the damage (Article 82, point 3). If multiple controllers or processors are responsible, each shall be held liable for the entire damage to ensure effective compensation for the data subject (Article 82, point 4).", 'full_answer': "Under the GDPR, liability for damages resulting from infringing processing is shared between controllers and processors based on their specific roles and actions. According to Article 82(2), any controller involved in processing is liable for the damage caused by processing that infringes the Regulation. In contrast, a processor's liability is limited; they are liable only when they have not complied with obligations specifically directed at processors or when they have acted outside or contrary to the lawful instructions provided by the controller. 

There is a provision for exemption: under Article 82(3), a controller or processor shall be exempt from liability if they can prove that they are not in any way responsible for the event that gave rise to the damage. 

Furthermore, to ensure the data subject receives effective compensation, Article 82(4) establishes that where more than one controller, more than one processor, or both are involved in the same processing and are found responsible under the aforementioned criteria, each individual controller or processor shall be held liable for the entire damage.", 'key_snippet': 'Any controller involved in processing shall be liable for the damage caused by processing', 'chunks': ['chapter VIII, article 82, point 2', 'chapter VIII, article 82, point 3', 'chapter VIII, article 82, point 4'], 'percentage': ['50', '25', '25']}
